column1: Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:59:40.393,2GDmuoMBv7QqA8hY1iOP,".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:59:41.764","Oct 9, 2022 @ 04:00:33.934",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:53:34.811,jWDguoMBv7QqA8hYchm6,".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:53:36.204","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:53:35.160",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:52:25.752,"_WDfuoMBv7QqA8hYYhfn",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:52:27.480","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:52:25.574",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:52:23.188,9GDfuoMBv7QqA8hYVhfq,".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:52:24.411","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:52:22.504",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

column1: Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:51:52.301,JWDeuoMBv7QqA8hY3hdJ,".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:51:53.546","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:51:51.624",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.143,"uWDYuoMBv7QqA8hY-g4O",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.926","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.517",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:03.744,"t2DYuoMBv7QqA8hY-g4O",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.926","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.516",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:44:19.453,"jWDYuoMBv7QqA8hY-Q7s",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.926","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.476",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:44:15.089,"hGDYuoMBv7QqA8hY-Q7s",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.926","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.474",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:43:54.550,"Z2DYuoMBv7QqA8hY-Q64",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.926","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.427",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:43:52.170,"EGDYuoMBv7QqA8hY-Q5e",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.700","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.340",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:43:47.133,"-WDYuoMBv7QqA8hY-Q1e",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.698","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.334",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:43:38.277,"xWDYuoMBv7QqA8hY-Q0x",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.694","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.291",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:43:34.338,"tGDYuoMBv7QqA8hY-Q0x",".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.693","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:25.287",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

column1: Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:43:27.868,jWDYuoMBv7QqA8hY9Q0B,".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:31.289","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:24.214",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing","-",start,"-","-","-","x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.

This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:43:16.504,MGDYuoMBv7QqA8hY9A17,".ds-winlogbeat-8.4.2-2022.09.27-000001","-","cf3699d7-5cb1-463f-a85f-a07c0632c54a","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","b5f6a7eb-024c-49d7-a722-2c9d1ee679a8","DESKTOP-STCA0K7",winlogbeat,"8.4.2","1.12.0","logged-in",authentication,4624,"Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:30.932","Oct 9, 2022 @ 03:45:24.076",event,security,success,"Microsoft-Windows-Security-Auditing",start,"x86_64","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","3a59bcc1-dab3-4fea-87c6-2dbb28db6023","fe80::d09e:33bc:93fc:2ba7, 10.0.2.15, fe80::bd6f:3885:d011:5ab0, 192.168.50.7","08:00:27:7c:f3:ae, 08:00:27:e4:bd:9d","DESKTOP-STCA0K7","19044.1889",windows,"10.0.19041.1889 (WinBuild.160101.0800)","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation","Windows 10 Enterprise Evaluation",windows,windows,"10.0",information,"An account was successfully logged on.
This event is generated when a logon session is created. It is generated on the computer that was accessed.

The subject fields indicate the account on the local system which requested the logon. This is most commonly a service such as the Server service, or a local process such as Winlogon.exe or Services.exe.
The logon type field indicates the kind of logon that occurred. The most common types are 2 (interactive) and 3 (network).
The New Logon fields indicate the account for whom the new logon was created, i.e. the account that was logged on.
The network fields indicate where a remote logon request originated. Workstation name is not always available and may be left blank in some cases.
The impersonation level field indicates the extent to which a process in the logon session can impersonate.
The authentication information fields provide detailed information about this specific logon request.

column2: - Logon GUID is a unique identifier that can be used to correlate this event with a KDC event.
- Transited services indicate which intermediate services have participated in this logon request.
- Package name indicates which sub-protocol was used among the NTLM protocols.
